                        "content": "The nurse in a primary health care provider setting is assessing a client who is there for an annual examination. After weighing and measuring the client, the nurse calculates the client’s body mass index (BMI) and determines that the client falls into the morbidly obese category. Which BMI value supports this assessment finding?",
                        "subjectId": "ad5ab04c79144c0ea9b83385308c3b1d",
                        "difficultyIds": "c2472dbaf30269ec1d4a4af474a31869",
                        "difficulty": "考试范围-Understanding 理解",
                        "textAnalysis": "Rationale:\nObesity is defined as an increase in body weight beyond the body’s physical requirements that results in an abnormal accumulation of fat cells. Primary obesity, the more common type of obesity, results from excess calorie intake over energy expenditure. Secondary obesity has various other causes, including congenital anomalies, metabolic problems, central nervous system disorders, or certain medications. Body mass index (BMI) provides a measure of obesity by dividing a person’s weight in kilograms by the square of the person’s height in meters. BMI categories consist of underweight, normal, overweight, obesity, and extreme obesity. Underweight is defined as a BMI of less than 18.5 kg/m2. Normal weight is defined as a BMI of 18.5 to 24.9 kg/m2. Overweight is defined as a BMI of 25.0 to 29.9 kg/m2. Obesity is defined as a BMI of 30.0 to 39.9 kg/m2. Morbid or extreme obesity is defined as a BMI greater than or equal to 40.0 kg/m2. Option 1 would be considered overweight. Option 2 would be considered normal weight. Option 3 would be considered obese, but not morbidly obese. Therefore, option 4 is considered a morbidly obese BMI and is the correct answer.",
