                        "type": "1",
                        "version": 0,
                        "content": "The nurse is assessing an obese female client for risk factors of metabolic syndrome. Which client data would the nurse determine are risk factors for metabolic syndrome? Select all that apply.",
                        "subjectId": "ad5ab04c79144c0ea9b83385308c3b1d",
                        "difficultyIds": "11797937e327eb6d913faa80427c566b",
                        "difficulty": "考试范围-Analyzing 分析",
                        "textAnalysis": "Rationale:\nObesity is a condition in which body weight is beyond the body’s physical requirements. Obesity increases the risk of metabolic syndrome. Metabolic syndrome is a cluster of risk factors that increase a person’s risk of cardiovascular disease, stroke, and diabetes. Abnormal findings that support a diagnosis of metabolic syndrome include obesity, hypertension, abnormal serum lipid levels, and abnormal blood glucose levels. The diagnostic measures for metabolic syndrome differ between males and females. Three of the five following criteria must be present for metabolic syndrome to be diagnosed: waist circumference greater than 35 inches (89 cm) in females and greater than 40 inches (102 centimeters) in males; triglycerides greater than 150 mg/dL (1.7 mmol/L) or drug treatment for high triglycerides; high-density lipoprotein (HDL) cholesterol less than 40 mg/dL (0.9 mmol/L) in males and less than 50 mg/dL (1.1 mmol/L) in females or drug treatment for hyperlipidemia; systolic blood pressure equal to or greater than 130 mm Hg, diastolic blood pressure equal to or greater than 85 mm Hg or treatment for hypertension; or fasting blood glucose greater than or equal to 100 mg/dL (5.6 mmol/L). The blood pressure in option 1 is below 130/85 mm Hg and is not a risk factor for metabolic syndrome. The serum triglyceride level in option 3 is below 150 mg/dL (1.7 mmol/L) and is not a risk factor for metabolic syndrome. The waist circumference for a female client in option 4 is below 35 inches (89 cm) and is not a risk factor for metabolic syndrome. The fasting blood glucose in option 2 is elevated and is above 100 mg/dL (5.6 mmol/L). The waist circumference in option 5 is above 35 inches (89 cm) for a female client. Therefore, options 2 and 5 are risk factors for metabolic syndrome.",
                        "id": "fcffdf41040a4a30b68434a767a1e437",
                        "mark": "0",
                        "collectionState": "0"
                    }
                ]
            },
